<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-06-20T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-06-20T03:00:00-05:00" n="482" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.001 L 76/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-06-20T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 20,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received June 20—9:47
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>273. Your 148, June 16, 4 p.m. Diplomatic body meeting this morning
                            unanimously accepted form of reply which I had drafted merely
                            acknowledging receipt of notification new President of accession.</p>
                        <p>Chang Tso-lin and Wu Pei-fu’s representatives have reached an agreement.
                            In 24 hours 18th and 19th, 358 cars loaded with guns, equipment and
                            horses belonging to Chang’s army left Shanhaikwan and Chang’s troops in
                            large numbers are passing beyond wall on foot.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
